Evergreen is a sweet cuddly little girl that is very shy till she gets to know you.  Once she does know you, she is like glue to you.  She wants to be close, and snuggles in tight at night in bed. Evergreen also likes playing with toys, chewing on bones, and will occasionally find something not appropriate to chew on, but is easily redirected to the correct chew toy.  She gets along well with other dogs once she gotten to know them and their habits.  It may take her a few hours to get through the warm up process though.  This little girl is also house trained and really enjoys meal time.  She is not a high activity dog.  Because she is so shy, we have her listed as "not great with kids."  This cutie is about 2 years old.

Oh Mavis - when you are a foster parent sometimes you get a dog that is so special and sweet that you know letting them go it going to be extra hard. That is Mavis for her foster family. Sweet Mavis came to us in rough shape. She had serious eye disease and had to have both eyes removed. After lots of TLC Mavis is ready to start the new year off with her forever family. Mavis is house trained, beyond sweet, dogs well with other dogs and has figured out this blind thing like a champ.

Esther came to our rescue with a huge hernia, mammoth tumors and needed to be spayed. She struggled with gaining weight and an infection but now she has healed and is at a healthy weight! 
Esther loves to lay around and cuddle on the sofa. She would love to meet a new companion and have a forever home. She is so cute with her big airplane ears when she looks up and is very sweet. She doesn't bark or whine only grunts and moans.  She just is not a complainer. She is working on her potty training and will go potty outside when taken out. She loves to go for walks and walks good on a leash. Esther is fine with other dogs and cats around as long as she can sit with you too. She does have some seeing issues but finds her way around the house and outside just fine.

Nic is a smart boy who is happy to learn new tricks. He is new to the program so we are learning more about him but we do know that he is going to need leash training and loves an opportunity to bolt out a door. Nic is heart worm positive and will be receiving treatment at CSRA expense.

Italians use the term Alora to mean 'it will be fine or just be calm'. Our sweet Alora embodies her names meaning in all ways. She came to us with puppies and has proved to have a calm happy demeanor through all the changes. Everyone who meets Alora falls in love with her. Alora will not be available until mid February but we wanted to give you plenty of time to get your applications in, this girl is a true gem. Her foster mom has this to say about her "Alora is no more than 2 years old and very healthy. Good with other dogs and humans of all ages. Have not observed her with cats. She is energetic and loves walks and playing chase when she can find a playmate. Not a ton of obedience training but is smart as a whip and learns quickly. She is the sweetest soul. She loves to cuddle. She is house broken and trustworthy in the house. No destructive behavior, although she does not love being confined. She'd be a great family 
pet or companion for any active lifestyle.'

Sweet Patsy is living a life she couldn't imagine in just a few weeks ago. She is being smothered in love, attention, vet care and a safe place to recuperate and get ready for her forever family. While we are still learning about her we do know that Patsy has had a hard life, so much so that she lost one ear and is going to take some time to heal from untreated issues.

McKay arrived with a history of neglect.  He has been with CSRA for over (6) months and thanks to a loving and patient foster home,  has received the love and attention he needed.  Although he has come a long way, he will require a very specific home environment.  

McKay can be the ONLY dog in residence, he is scared of large dogs, is bossy with male dogs and does not engage in playing with any dog.

McKay requires an experienced home who will spend the time it will take to work with him.  He has a lot of energy and is not a coach potato.

Just look at me now! I am still fighting the itchies, butÂ  my skin is getting better everyday. I still have a few more weeks of special treats to make it all better, but I don't mind. I have my own special chair to stretch out on and other dogs to keep me company. while I wait.Â 

Molly is a sweet 11 y/o Brittany/ lab mix who likes to go for walks and cuddle on the couch. She is great with other dogs and cats and likes her baths. She does take medicine for her allergies.

Molly is currently unavailable for adoption until her health (allergy related) has improved.   

Molly is being fostered in the Austin area.

Rocky came us in 2010 from the shelter in San Angelo, where he was surrendered after he was the âropeâ in a game of tug of war between two pit bulls and his previous owner could not afford to take him to the vet. Rocky had some puncture wounds, but he healed nicely and you would never know anything ever happened to him, except he is a little more scared of large dogs. He was then adopted out and lived happily with his owner for years. His owner sadly suffered a stroke and Rocky had to come back into rescue and look for another home.  
Heâs a big dog in a little body. He used to play and run with other dogs (mostly smaller types) and with the two cats in his foster home, but he would probably need someone to initiate playing with him. But he also loves to kick back with his human and is an excellent cuddler. He enjoys giving kisses, going for car rides, and keeping his teeth clean by gnawing on bully sticks given to him. He walks with confidence on leash and thoroughly enjoys walks in the neighborhood and even occasional outings to the dog park. Rocky visited a foster home with kids and did well with them. 

Rocky is looking for a home to call his very own.  Heâs a sweet natured little guy with lots of love to give. A home with another small dog to play with would be ideal, but he would probably do just as well being the center of your attention. If you are looking for that special little ball of joy thatâs loveable and cuddly then this little guy is for you.  Please fill out an application soon because heâs already charming everyone he meets and he likely wonât be available for long! Adoption fee is $200. If you are interested in adopting Rocky, please read our Frequently Asked Questions before completing the adoption application . The application and general information can also be found at: www.smallchancerescue.com .

Meet Adopt-A-Bull Barney!

Barney is dog social, crate trained, house trained and so incredibly eager to please. He takes treats super gently and is always looking for someone to throw some toys around with him. He LOVES to explore anywhere he goes, barely taking his nose off the ground until he's sniffed everything. Barney's stout little body, goofy antenna ear (one never lays down), gentle nature and loving personality make him a total catch to one lucky family!

Barney is heartworm positive so he is currently going through heartworm treatment to get rid of them, but is totally healthy otherwise. He is up to date on his vaccinations and will be neutered once his heartworm treatment is complete.

If you would like to add Barney to your family, please take the first step and fill out our online adoption application: http://love-a-bull.org/adopt/adoption-application/ OR email adopt@love-a-bull.org

Did you make a New Years Resolution to get more exercise? Let Jill help you with that! Jill is a happy, frolicking puppy love bug who loves to explore everything! She is incredibly smart, alert and eager to please. She would very likely excel in agility or therapy work. Jill loves children and playing with other dogs then snuggling on the couch at night. She is crate trained and well on her way to house-breaking. We donât know who her doggy parents are but she has the busy nose, temperament, size and need for exercise of a French Brittany or Springer and an incredibly silky coat. If you need an exercise buddy and have a good throwing arm for fetch, Jill is for you! CSRA requires that our dogs be in foster care for a minimum of one week, so Jill will be available after 2/3/18.

Do you like to snuggle? Are you looking for a beautiful, brilliant young lady to tell you what to do with all your free time? Then Midge might just be the girl for you!
 Midge is a quick learner, devoted to her humans, and loves to play with other dogs and children. There might be debate as to if her parents are Springer, French Brittany, Cocker or Labrador but no doubt they were smart with inquisitive noses. Midge is a leader not a follower so would be happiest with a doggie sibling that lets her be the boss, sheâs not aggressive, just confident in her Princess-ness. Harry was turned in a stray right before Thanksgiving. Given the winter we are having, we are all grateful he got to the shelter when he did. As you can see from his before pictures, Harry was hairless, with a bad case of mange.  Harry had the non-contagious mange so he went to a foster home right away. Fast forward a few weeks of baths (which he was good with) and antibiotics to Harry today.  He was just neutered and had a dental on the 26th (Merry Christmas Harry!) so he is now ready to find his permanent home.  Yes, his hair still has a way to go but that is just superficial. You can see his coat is a beautiful brindle color and when it comes back fully, he will be gorgeous.
 
Harryâs housetraining is a work in progress.  His foster mom has already seen an improvement in the short time since his neuter.  He does give clear signals when he needs to potty. He does fine being crated. He currently is staying in a home with four dogs, ranging from 30 lbs. to 8 lbs., and three cats.  Harry gets along well with all of them. He is savvy and has figured out who to play with and who to avoid.  He absolutely loves to run in the backyard and he enjoys playing with anyone animal who will play with him. The three year old small male dog and Harry wrestle and play constantly. He will eventually wear himself out and then likes to curl up beside you for a nap. He also enjoys being petted.
 
Harry has met and got along well with older children, and weâre continuing to introduce him to more people. Due to his small size, He should be supervised around small kids or large dogs so he doesnât get hurt. If you have patience to continue his training, you will be rewarded with a goofy, loving little guy who will make you laugh every day. Adoption fee is $200.
If you are interested in adopting, please read our Frequently Asked Questions before completing the adoption application .
The application and general information can also be found at: www.smallchancerescue.com .

Ginger was pulled from a high kill shelter in the Killeen area from a shelter that is not able to adopt out pitties. She was found as a stray and her gentle, loving nature makes her just about the perfect pup!

Ginger is incredibly calm and mellow. She'd much rather curl up in your lap rather than play with toys. She is dog social, cat social and LOVES people, including children. Ginger is house trained and walks incredibly well on a leash. If you are looking for a cuddle bug to curl up with, then Ginger is your girl!

If you'd like to add Ginger to your family, please fill out our online adoption application: http://love-a-bull.org/adopt/adoption-application/ OR email adopt@love-a-bull.org

Kahli is a playful, loving girl who knows how to let her personality shine! She loves going for walks and exploring and of course playing her favorite toy, a tennis ball. She is dog social, cat social and loves getting her belly rubbed by children. Kahli is also house trained, crate trained and up-to-date on all her vaccinations.

If you would like to add Kahli to your family, please fill out our online adoption application: http://love-a-bull.org/adopt/adoption-application/ OR email adopt@love-a-bull.org

Meet Adopt-A-Bull, Jim!!

This goofy boy was pulled from a high kill shelter in Killeen, TX and as you can tell has had a rough go of things. In addition to being underweight, he came in with a host of internal parasites and unfortunately also has heartworms. BUT, none of that has dampened his zest for life!

Jim is dog social and loves to run and play! He also enjoys sniffing every part of his surroundings. Jim is going to bring a smile to one lucky families face for the rest of their lives.

If you are interested in adding Jim to your family, please fill out our online adoption application: http://love-a-bull.org/adopt/adoption-application/ OR email adopt@love-a-bull.org

She is very happily excited to meet new people and dogs.  And it sometimes takes her a few minutes to calm down.  I think sheâll mellow when sheâs a bit older.  When she has decided that sheâs thoroughly welcomed you, she curls up into a ball and snuggles on your lap or finds a spot on the cushion you are leaning against and snuggles behind your neck. 

Kitty loves to play!  She and my dog chase each other around the house and around the yard.  And they usually have a wrestling match in the evenings after dinner.  She loves to play with her human friends, too.  She almost has âfetchâ down.  Sheâll chase a squeaky toy and bring it back to you - for a while anyway.  I think sheâd be great with kids and sheâd adore them.  And I think sheâd be happiest if she had a dog sibling who also liked to play.

She loves to run around outside and sit in the sun.  Sheâs pretty independent and will enjoy the sunshine even on her own.  Her back yard is her domain and she is quick enough to let the squirrels know whoâs boss.

Sheila is my hero. She's absolutely fearless as she makes her way in her darkened world. The first night she was exploring the back yard to make sure there weren't lizards or bunnies invading her territory. She hasn't been exposed to cats but she likes the deer that feed outside the fence, even going up to them and poking her nose through the fence so she can get acquainted. She maneuvers quite well around the house and yard, responding to "Watch" when she looks like she is going to hit something and then she changes direction.

She makes her wishes known by coming to me and nuzzling to let me know it's time to go outside. But my favorite is when she does her happy dance at mealtimes. She does a little growl and then she turns round and round on her hind legs, tail going ninety miles an hour (that's unofficial but I have it on good authority). She's easy going about bedtime, she likes the big bed but is perfectly content in her own bed as well. She is happy with other dogs but if they try to get between her and her treats, she lets them know that isn't acceptable, food is very important to Sheila!

I had never thought about dealing with a blind dog and was little apprehensive, but she has taught me that it's really no different from a sighted dog, they all need to be loved and appreciated. If you give Sheila a chance for her forever home, you won't be disappointed. I think she will amaze you the way she has me.
